The wines of the “Domaine de la Romanee Conti,” because of their scarcity and magnificence, have always been collector’s items among serious wine drinkers. It is therefore no ordinary event when 16 of its wines of excellent vintage years are offered by a single wine merchant at such relatively modest prices. The Domaine de la Romanee Conti, which estate bottles every- thing it sells, consists of five vineyards; all of Romanee Conti, all of La Tache, goodly portions of Richebourg, Grand Echezeaux and Echezeaux. The crowning jewel of the Domaine is the peerless Romanee Conti vineyard (it consists of only five acres which brought as much as $56,000 back in 1868 and is consistently the most expensive red wine on the world market). Almost any of these wines will prove absolutely superb for immediate drinking, but since they are the most long lived of red wines, they will reach even greater heights after they have matured further in your cellars.
